    <p> Since the beds in hostels in Sydney are extremely expensive and bad to get between Christmas and New Year's Eve, I decided to get a room in a shared apartment. In addition, I didn't feel like having to change the room every few days for 3 months because you wouldn't get it any other way. </p>
<p> Well, so I looked for what the internet had to say on the topic of WG rooms. I stumbled across the website directly <a href="https://flatmates.com.au/" target="_blank"> Flatmates.com.au </a> which means so much as roommates and <a href="https://gumtree.com.au/" target="_blank"> Gumtrree.com.au </a> what a side for classified ads is. On this website I also promptly found one or the other nice offer. Some of them sounded almost too good to be true. I replied to some ads directly via the website and asked if the respective room was still free and whether I could take a look at it. </p>
<h2 style="display:inline;"> It stinks after fraud </h2>
<p> I promptly received an answer to one of these messages. This came from a gentleman named Craig. This informed me that the apartment would still be free and I would like to report quickly if I was interested. Since this address is in the middle of the city center, of course, I replied promptly and asked again about a viewing date. </p>
